My meme

The four squares was the four main components of the inspiration meme. I recreated this meme by changing both the pictures in the meme, from Winnie the Pooh to photos of people. I also changed the width and height of each boxes. I kept the font the same but reversed the colors of the text and background. The text was also a key feature that was changed.

library(magick)

#MAKING A MEME

# square one
normal_person <- image_read("https://as2.ftcdn.net/v2/jpg/00/52/52/91/1000_F_52529137_GxqDGxGqZxCwxpQQVdrPF31oypP1s5Qy.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)

#square two
meme_text <- image_blank(width = 500, 
                          height = 300, 
                          color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Making\nmemes",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 60,
                 font = "Arial",
                 gravity = "center")

# square three
mind_blown <- image_read("https://t4.ftcdn.net/jpg/05/74/26/31/360_F_574263101_TJBaEd9BGd36eO1TlPhnl8apExNEdq8n.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)

# square four
stats_text <- image_blank(width = 500, 
                       height = 300, 
                       color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Making memes\nin stats220",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 60,
                 font = "Arial",
                 gravity = "center")

# making each row

# first row
top_row <- image_append(c(normal_person, meme_text))

# second row
bottom_row <- image_append(c(mind_blown, stats_text))

# putting it all together 
meme <- c(top_row, bottom_row) %>%
  image_append(stack = TRUE) %>%
  image_scale(800)
# MAKING A GIF

# creating each frame
frame1 <-  image_blank(width = 500, 
                       height = 300, 
                       color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Making\nmemes",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 60,
                 font = "Arial",
                 gravity = "center")

frame2 <- image_read("https://as2.ftcdn.net/v2/jpg/00/52/52/91/1000_F_52529137_GxqDGxGqZxCwxpQQVdrPF31oypP1s5Qy.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)

frame3 <- image_blank(width = 500, 
                      height = 300, 
                      color = "#000000") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Making memes\nin stats220",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 60,
                 font = "Arial",
                 gravity = "center")

frame4 <- image_read("https://t4.ftcdn.net/jpg/05/74/26/31/360_F_574263101_TJBaEd9BGd36eO1TlPhnl8apExNEdq8n.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(500)

frame5 <- image_blank(width = 500, 
                      height = 300, 
                      color = "#1155FF") %>%
  image_annotate(text = ":-)",
                 color = "#FFFFFF",
                 size = 60,
                 font = "Arial",
                 gravity = "center")

# putting the frames in order
frames <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4, frame5)

# creating an animation
gif <- image_animate(frames, fps = 1)

Creativity

My project demonstrates creativity by using data visualization techniques, CSS styles and two meme creations that intertwines humor and my new learnings.

I used a variety of colors from the color wheel when altering texts and background. I also changed the size, font and gravity of text and images.

I used many different CSS styles to make the html file visually and aesthetically appealing; not only background-color, but also padding, font-weight and text-decoration.

I used a new feature that was not taught in lectures to create hyperlinks, clickable through text, which I found to be much more space-friendly and readable.
